1.body: "ugggggh" Lucas groans, as he scrambles once more for his phone on the nightstand. He grabs at the charging cable and the phone crashes to the hardwood floor, making even more noise, and ensuring his wife is definitely also now awake. Her exasperated heavy sigh removes any doubt. Lucas swipes at the screen three times until the funk-jazz ringtone finally stops, leaving only the bright glare of blue light screaming 4:38 am. The ringtone was supposed to make it slightly less painful when he is paged, but after hearing it for the third time since midnight, it has definitely lost any of the mild humour it once had. "What...now..." he complains to himself; fumbling through the familiar sequence of two-factor security checks, feature-crippled corporate browser navigation, and in-house ticketing system to get to any indication of what so desperately needs his attention. It's now 4:40. and the last shred of optimism for an issue that can be resolved from the comfort of bed is gone. One foot, then the next reluctantly hits the floor and he trudges towards the spare room where his company laptop awaits. "No..it's not playtime now Sugar" he whispers in the general direction of the house cat; who has turned its initial confusion at the change of routine into eager readiness for playtime, an early feeding, or anything other than what must be done in the spare room. The sun has already started its daily ascent, slowly illuminating the dining room and the makeshift home office with a warm glow that signals his chance of returning to sleep is quickly vanishing. There was a time when Lucas would be walking these floor boards towards the back door on his way for morning exercise. Some mornings it was a bike ride along the local river; sometimes a brisk walk to the peak of the nearby hill that overlooks the parks that surround the city. Usually only a podcast kept him company, though sometimes his wife Jeanine would join him. Those walks together were a distant memory now as the monthly occurence of a week of night time paging ensured the three other "off weeks" were critical for recovery and preservation. The glare of the operating system logo prys both eyes wide open while his laptop loads. The downgraded ticket from a little over an hour ago when he was last awake refreshes on one screen. "Pending upgrade" it flashes, indicating he has a little over two hours until the pager is guaranteed to fire again when "business hours" resume. Right now though he has to keep his attention on the latest issue, which has finally loaded the full details on his second screen. "Cannot delete old items from the portal" reads the title. The ticket details explain a chaotic cry for urgent help from 'Liddy'. "Well that explains the 18 unread Slack notifications" Lucas mumbles, simultaneously loading the service dashboard and acknowledging he's investigating the ticket. When the dashboard does eventually load, he's greeted by an array of graphs measuring every detail of the service. He skims through disk usage, CPU utilization, inode usage, canary success rates, p99.99 latency measurements and API call volumes. The graphs have been a labour of love for Lucas and his team over the last few months since they took ownership of the service. Each graph has clear indications of the alarm level relevant to the graph, direct links to relevant runbooks, and an annotated history of significant and recent events they have seen. The graphs share one other important factor - they all indicate perfect health. "What the..." he groans, in a mixture of disbelief, fear of an issue he has no metrics for, and the resignation that he's no closer to resting. "Hi Liddy - can you please describe the business impact, the steps you have taken to resolve, and provide details of the items you unsuccessfully attempted to delete, thanks! Lucas" he posts to the ticket, before switching over to the Slack window while he awaits a reply. Intuition has served him well again - the 18 notifications are all from Liddy, starting at 3:56 and ending a few minutes before the dulcet Jazz tones dragged him back into his semi-conscious early morning state. The first few messages are cheery; a warm good morning and friendly how-do-you-do without an indication of the urgency of the ticket. A stranger would assume Liddy and Lucas are long time friends, but they have certainly never met. The next message - 8 minutes later is not so pleasant. In fact this one way conversation peaked before 4am, and by 4:30 had devolved into a different number of question marks once a minute. Each of Lucas' three screens has open an issue he has worked on during the night. On the right most screen is the ticket opened by Liddy; the window flashes due to an update and draws Lucas' attention. The reply makes little sense to him - it talks of products sold on the external website, while Lucas builds and maintains internal tools and services for other software teams - some that are indeed found via an internal portal. As he re-reads the ticket description, the pieces of the puzzle fall in to place - Liddy has opened the ticket to the wrong team. Tomorrow - or rather, later today - Lucas will find a new ticket group was created with a name close enough to his own that has caused the confusion. He updates the ticket and re-routes it to the correct group before noticing that the queue of 10 open tickets from yesterday has grown to 35 in the last hour. The fix is quick and the misplaced tickets are moved to their rightful owners. As the clock ticks past 5am he happily closes the lid of his laptop. The CPU fans spin to a stop - no longer needing to cool the hardware struggling to keep up with the browser full of abandonded tabs. Lucas' head rests momentarily on the laptop - partly from exhaustion, and partly as a physical prevention for it to interrupt his morning again. "Dammit..." he sighs as he remembers the other issue that will escalate in less than two hours. Lucas thinks for a moment. "No, screw it" he defiantly declares to the room, shuffling slowly over to the old couch at the back of the house before collapsing on its worn out springs. The couch is the furthermost place from the bedroom Jeanine is (hopefully) asleep in, so the inevitable 7am paging will surely not wake her. No need then for the regular 6:30 morning alarm either he realizes, quickly disabling it so he can soak up an extra 30 minutes sleep. "At least I will be off-call in two days" he thinks to himself, as he places a throw cushion over his weary eyes and waits for sleep or exhaustion to render him unconscious. It feels like five minutes has past when the Jazz tune rings out from between the couch cushions, growing increasingly louder like an impatient hungry child. Sugar scrambles as finally the pager is silenced. 9:12am. "9:12! What happened to the 7am wake up page? Where is Jeanine? How can four hours have passed already?!" Lucas wonders. His head is pounding as if he had enjoyed one too many beers last night; the heat of the sun compounding the pain, and adding to the nausea of sleep deprivation. There are no details of the issue on the paging notification, again. This time there doesn't need to be though - Lucas can see it comes from his new boss - Dean. Lucas heads to the kitchen to grab a glass of water, knowing it may be a while before he can leave his seat once he gets started on the latest issue. "What's up boss?" he pings to Dean. No reply. Lucas waits, keeping himself busy with reading the titles of new tickets that have arrived since 5am. To his surprise, the ticket he expected to wake him is no where to be seen. Still no response from Dean. The forest green dot next to his name indicates he is online, but he must be preocupied. Lucas waits another minute before getting up to turn on the coffee machine. A good shot of caffeine will surely help shake the haze from the morning. The air fills with the smell of freshly ground beans, but that is as close to becoming a cup of coffee as they will get. Midway through the grind the reply from Dean arrived on Lucas' phone, and he rushed back to the spare room to reply. "Where were you!?" the first message ironically reads. "You were supposed to present our metrics at the Ops review meeting at 9". A wave of defeat rolls over Lucas, different from the times his pager broke his sleep, but equally crushing of his spirit. The Ops review is a weekly meeting to review operational health. The review is attended by senior managers and lead engineers from across the company and gives engineers a spotlight to shine on improvements the team has made and to seek advice or help where services need improving. Lucas' skip manager had volun-told Lucas he needed to present for twenty minutes today late in the afternoon yesterday. Lucas knew exactly what he wanted to present and was looking forward to the opportunity. In that moment he also knew exactly what missing the meeting meant. "I slept through my alarm..." he types, before pausing, and deleting the words. "I'm wiped out from three pages last night and missed the call" he reluctantly replies. "Is there any time left to present?" he questions. The reply is delayed again. Lucas waits, starring motionless at the screen, his stomach churning from missing breakfast and the ominous feeling of missing the review. "No, Swami took care of it, wrapping up now, chat later" comes the reply. A mix of relief for his team, and loss for the personal opportunity fills the rest of the morning. By late afternoon the pager has finally managed a full hour of silence, so Lucas decides to sign off for a few hours. Several days later Lucas and Dean are both working from the office and decide to take a walk to a nearby coffee shop while they hold their regular 1:1. Dean is new to the team, however he has been with the company for almost as long as Lucas, and they have agreed on the direction of the team in most conversations to date. Dean is a polite character with a skill for listening to problems rather than jumping to solutions. The clanging of mugs and background chatter in the popular coffee shop force them to talk louder than they would otherwise. Dean makes small chat and they both avoid talking about the business around the other coffee addicts awaiting their fix. When the coffee order arrives they head across the road to a bench over looking the dog park. "What's on your mind?" asks Dean. "Oncall...the ops review I missed..." Lucas says, screwing his face up and assuming Dean is watching the goofy Labrador playing with a tired old rope. Lucas briefly wonders if his face bears some resemblance to the rope after the last week. "...and what else?" Dean probes. "promo" Lucas reluctantly sighs. The dogs continue to bark and a cyclist zips past close to the bench, cutting the silence that had started to form after Lucas' reply. "Well, which is the biggest challenge?" Dean asks. "Well, they're all somewhat related, I think" Lucas quips. "The Ops review was important...for the team and for me. I know Marni asked me to present it for a reason, and I know she still doesn't trust our team yet". "True, on both accounts" Dean confirms. Lucas pauses, slightly shocked at how quickly Dean's response came. "I have been putting in everything I can to get our operations under control, to get all the new hires ramped up, and to get the design for the new platform ready...but there just aren't enough hours in the day to make it all happen" he explains in a mix of frustration and mild desperation. "That's correct" Dean confidently says, eyes still fixated on the Labrador across the road. "So, how can I help?" he asks.

4.body: @startmindmap apophenia -- Things to lean in to --- Coaching and Mentoring ---- Which is which ---- Coaching ----- Track it, make renewing it a forceful act ----- Set goals ---- Mentoring ----- Be a human; sometimes a sounding board; solution vs an ear ----- Put down the kool aid ----- Admit when you don't know ---- Coaching others ----- Socratic method ----- Share; but don't over extend ----- Praise in public, coach in private ----- Unconsciously unskilled; consciously unskilled; consciously skilled; unconsciously skilled ----- Actions are negative/positive, not the character that creates them ----- No budget on compliments and thank yous ----- Set limits and boundaries ----- 1:1 format: What's on your mind, and what else, what's the real challenge, what do you want from me, how can I help, yea to this then no to what, what was most useful ----- Phrases: Thank you for pointing that out ----- Phrases: can you help me understand ----- Phrases: "help me understand" to open and unlearn ----- Listening not solving ----- Acknowledge their change/growth - offset with previous behavior ----- Publicly acknowledge wins and turnarounds ----- Psychological safety ---- Coaching yourself ----- Growth mindset ----- Not everyone can speak your language yet ----- Things look like they're getting worse when you're getting better ----- Brag doc ----- Keep a log; keep working docs ----- Calendar time for important tasks: sending praise, keeping promises, reading docs, updating documentation ----- Know your boundaries: topics, stretch/time; review them frequently ----- You're never as bad as you think you are; or as good as others think you are ----- There will always be more work tomorrow; but not more of tonight ----- Phrases: this is what it looks like ----- Phrases: progress is ugly/messy ---- Managing Up ----- Interested not interesting ----- Give feedback on what is going well; when you see they're trying new things ----- Give thanks for opportunities and support ----- Define expectations early; review often ----- Do they have full visibility of your work / non-task work? ----- Do they talk to the right people that can give feedback on your performance? ----- Do they know how to (have they already) promoted someone to your next role? ----- Share calendar events for recurring tasks: perf review, promo data gathering ----- Help make your leadership chain successful; not failure proof ----- Escalations: what do they need? when do they think it is appropriate to go above them? ----- Be human; and don't forget they are too ----- Phrases: how do I help you? ----- Phrases: when do you want to hear from me? ----- Phrases: what would a bad outcome be for you? ----- Phrases: what do you need to be successful? ----- Phrases: what is not working for you from me/my team? --- Become predictable / Speak the same lingo ---- How we work, how we oncall ---- Define the relationship early ---- How you do anything is how you do everything ---- Rumplestiltskin principle (to give a name is to have true power over it) ---- Swings and roundabouts --- Move fast / Get Shit Done ---- Hypothesis, experiment, review, iterate, fast ---- Code three times, so make the first time cheapest ---- Be wrong alot now to be right a lot later; Cunninghams law ---- Timeboxing until enough ambiguity has gone that you can estimate or reflect ---- Solve a small part of the problem to understand it better ---- Start with a small/easy one, then one/the hardest: to find boundaries ---- Bucketize the problem and find the long tail ---- Grandfathering ---- Let things fail; hero cowboy ---- Last responsible moment ---- Eisenhower matrix ---- Count, compute, compare, judge ---- Five is better than none, one is better than two ---- A rising tide lifts all boats ---- Mudmap ---- Do one thing, and do it well ---- The long pole ---- Perfect is the enemy of good enough ---- What if only half of this plan happens? ---- How frequent is it, or is it an edge case? ---- Trams, not smart ---- Raci; but be careful ---- Don't jump to a solution ---- Business use case & value ---- Make work visible; celebrate successes, review failures --- Understand the business ---- Understand business seasons/cycle ---- How does the business make money and how do you help that happen ---- Software archaeology ---- Postcard from the future ---- Reverse Conway maneuver ---- Say no if it isn't aligned with the mission ---- Timing is everything ---- Work is not your family ---- Hippo ---- Gemba - go where the work happens ---- Right message, right channel ---- Empty chair; customer in the room; say your customers name ---- Great products fill great needs ---- Focus on misery for improvement to sentiment ---- Will it make the boat go faster? -- Make things better --- Boy scout rule --- Reverse broken windows theory --- Coding/writing katas --- Pegs n poky (peer recognition ideas) --- Mock ops event -- Lookout! --- Measurements become goals --- Your normal changes if you're growing --- Listen to all feedback and advice; implement incrementally; seek more --- Beware advice of those with no skin in the game --- Solving an easier problem when it's too hard --- Cargo cult --- A compromise can only be between two valid choices --- Delegation without empowerment will fail -- Grit / Suck it up / Turn the ship around / Build a team --- Tax bad behaviours --- Promote those that model the ideal behavior --- Never: "omg you don't know about X" (training people not to come to you) --- Fox in the hen house --- Embrace the suck --- Slow is smooth, smooth is fast --- Say thank you alot, and mean it --- Meet them where they're at --- You can't help others if you haven't helped yourself first --- Pariah in the house --- Embrace, extend, extinguish --- Tuckmans model --- Trust but verify --- Mastery autonomy and purpose --- People process technology --- Set expectations early and continuously --- Relationships need credit in the account before you withdraw --- Principle of charity; interpret most favourably --- Assume best intent --- If it were easy or solved they wouldn't need you --- Does it need to be said? Does it need to be said by me? Does it need to be said by me right now? --- Hill to die on; disagree and commit -- Software --- Promises and apologies --- Tech fraud vs tech debt --- Afferent Vs efferent coupling --- Advent of code / ops cookie of fortune -- Meta --- Everything is on a spectrum; tradeoffs --- Price point; if you set it low you're indicating what it's worth --- Shu ha ri --- Level/title doesn't indicate where in their band/growth they are; could be LE or TT --- No false gods; Don't assume highest level/most tenured is infallible --- Elephant in the army (war elephant) --- Notes: Elephant - making a lot of noise but not doing anything --- The team donkey ++ Adventure @endmindmap
